  <main id="main" class="wrap layout">
    <article id="woolf" class="card">
      <header>
        <h2>Virginia Woolf</h2>
      </header>
      <p>Woolf writes with attention to inner life and passing time. <em>Mrs. Dalloway</em> and <em>To the Lighthouse</em> turn ordinary moments into structure. <em>A Room of One’s Own</em> still frames how we talk about creativity and space.</p>
    </article>

    <section id="baldwin" class="card">
      <h2>James Baldwin</h2>
      <p>Clear, steady, and unsparing. In <em>The Fire Next Time</em> and <em>Giovanni’s Room</em>, he looks at truth—public and private—and asks what honesty costs.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="orwell" class="card">
      <h2>George Orwell</h2>
      <p>Plain style used precisely. <em>1984</em> and <em>Animal Farm</em> stay relevant because they question how language and power shape what counts as “true.”</p>
    </section>

    <aside id="morrison" class="card aside">
      <h3>Toni Morrison</h3>
      <p>Memory, love, and history threaded together. <em>Beloved</em> and <em>Song of Solomon</em> move with lyrical force while staying grounded in lived detail.</p>
    </aside>
  </main>

